# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: c-h-collyns
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:c-h-collyns/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:c-h-collyns/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] He became a vegetarian as a young man through reading the work of T.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] Bailey Walker and joined the Vegetarian Society in 1877.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] He worked as an analytical chemist in Manchester and for James Woolley, Sons and Co., manufacture chemists.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] Duncan had studied with Carl Remigius Fresenius.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] He was also a Fellow of the Chemical Society.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] In 1884, Duncan authored a pamphlet *The Chemistry of Foods*.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] It was republished as *The Chemistry of Food and Nutrition* by the Vegetarian Society in 1905.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] Forward noted that Duncan had given "valuable aid to the Vegetarian Society in connection with the chemistry of food, and has contributed many useful essays and papers on the subject".
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] Duncan was on the executive committee of the Vegetarian Society in 1880 and later served as a vice-president.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] In 1899, Duncan commented that "a grain of wheat contains everything that is required for nutrition and these constituents are in the right proportion, so that were it necessary we could live on wheatmeal bread and water alone".
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] He later moved to New South Wales, Australia but remained in contact with vegetarians in England and was an officer for the Vegetarian Society in 1935.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] He married Annie Margaret Allison in 1890.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] They had two children: Frank and Phyllis.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] Duncan died in Punchbowl, New South Wales in 1946, aged 90.
[src:c-h-collyns/a-w-duncan] He was privately cremated at Rockwood crematorium.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] He was educated at Christ Church, Oxford, and was admitted to orders in 1844.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] During 1844–1845 he was curate of St Mary Magdalen's Church, Oxford.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] From 1867 to 1874 he was Headmaster of the Grammar School at Wirksworth, Derbyshire.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] He was secretary of the British Temperance League which was the oldest national temperance organization in England.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] Collyns became a vegetarian in 1872 and joined the Vegetarian Society in September 1873.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] He later became a vice-president of the society.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] Collyns was also a member of the Anti-Compulsory Vaccination League, Anti-Narcotic League and the United Kingdom Alliance.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] He translated the works of Pacian published in the *Library of the Fathers* in 1844.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] He also translated Jean-Antoine Gleizes' *Thalysie*, but it was not published.
[src:c-h-collyns/c-h-collyns] He died age 65 in Sheffield on 8 July 1885.
